Version 1 - [Django][django]
============================

The very first time I tried to make _this_ website I had very little experience outside of editing raw HTML.
With my programming knowledge mainly based in [C++][cpp] and [Python][python], I did some research and settled on using the [Django][django] framework.

After going through all of tutorials and setting up a basic blog I fell at the hurdle of getting the thing hosted.
Whatever year it was when I attempted this, combined with my limited knowledge of all things server side, I found it hard to get a free/cheap solution for hosting the python back end.


Version 2 - [Flask][flask]
==========================

Having a database, users, online interface for publishing articles, etc. was all a bit much for a small toy website like this.
With some more research I found out about static websites and that lead me to the [Frozen Flask][frozenflask] project which generated static HTML  files for a app made with the [Flask][flask] micro framework.

[Flask][flask] seemed to fit my use case better than  [Django][django] and with a little work the static website output was easy to copy across to the [GitHub Pages][ghpages] branch of the [project][oldgithub].

With the ability to push the website straight to the free hosting I managed to get more structure and 'style' than Version 1.
A lot of iteration was done on this version and as I learned about all things _web_.

Version 2.5 - [Grunt][grunt]
----------------------------

As I made other toy websites such as [Interface Zero][interface] and [Presentations][presentations] I leverages the power of [Node.js][node] and [Grunt][grunt].
[Grunt][grunt] replaced all of the shell scripts that I had made for automating the tasks of running the static site generation.
As that was so easy to do, I also got packages to enable me to prettify and minimize parts of the website.
I also got a very nice package [grunt-gh-pages][gruntgh] which simplified pushing the dist files to the server.


Version 3 - [assemble.io][assemble]
===================================

When I lost the dev environment that I set up on a laptop to work with the [Flask][flask] project I stopped updating it.
When I wanted to make some improvements to the site I jumped into the code (specifically the template for the navbar) and I was completely lost!
A classic programmers error - expecting that the code would make sense in the future!

Seeing as there is very little traffic to the site I decided to just re-do the whole thing from scratch.

With node installed, there are only a few global package installs and then the website can be set up to run.
I currently have the dev environment running on Linux and Windows 7.
The built in task `grunt server` allows me to make 'live changes' to the locally server files greatly improving the work flow from my hashed together Flask and Grunt combo in Version 2.

The Future
==========

[assemble.io][assemble] is still being developed. In the future I will upgrade some of the code to make use of plugins written by the community and maybe write some more detailed write ups on how I get [assemble.io][assemble] to work for me.

